{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488635"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:50:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:50:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"497"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/497"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.74,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97832"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/497"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80387"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"431"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"540"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97832"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man with a history of type II diabetes mellitus presents with a two month history of blurring of vision. The only abnormality found is that shown in the photograph (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Scleritis","Episcleritis","Pterygium","Chalazion","Trachoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epterygium\u003C/strong\u003E is a wing-shaped, fibrovascular proliferation over the limbus of the cornea. It is a common condition which occurs more frequently in those who live in areas with high ultraviolet radiation, while also being associated with dry, hot, dusty, windy and smoky conditions. A pterygium is a degenerative process with no known aetiology, most commonly occuring on the nasal side of the cornea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA pterygium is typically present for months or years and may be associated with erythema, blurring of vision, diplopia and irritation or discomfort. Examination should include an assessment of visual acuity, extraoccular movements and a measurement of the pterygium to assess growth over time. A pterygium may impair visual fields and restrict movement. An important differential of a pterygium is ocular surface squamous neoplasia (OSSN), which can be differentiated based on its rapid progression and dysplastic features on examination (leucoplakia, raised mass, prominent blood vessels).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERetinoscopy may reveal any astigmatism caused by the pterygium, and corneal topography may detect associated distortion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConservative treatment may involve lubricating drops or non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drops (eg ketorolac trometamol), while surgical treatment is indicated when there is involvement of the visual axis, vision loss, restricted movements, dysplastic appearance and increasing size. If steroid drops are prescribed instead, regular checks of intra-ocular pressure are mandatory to prevent blinding secondary glaucoma. Patients must be counselled about the high risk of recurrence following surgical removal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Surgery is the only effective way of getting rid of a pterygium."],"references":["Hall AB. Understanding and managing pterygium. Community Eye Health. 2016;29(95):54-6."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80387"}},"question":{"data